1
00:00:01,230 --> 00:00:02,630
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,110 --> 00:00:13,130
I'm starting another project meant to make life easier for experimenters in the free-energy field.

3
00:00:14,150 --> 00:00:21,270
The block schematic shown in this picture is a power supply, universal for our experiments.

4
00:00:22,130 --> 00:00:25,450
Planned output voltage up to 1000 V.

5
00:00:25,450 --> 00:00:33,750
We'll also try out something new for me in this circuit — working with opto-drivers.

6
00:00:36,010 --> 00:00:39,270
So why do we need a circuit like this?

7
00:00:39,470 --> 00:00:46,790
The thing is, you can of course get by with store-bought power supplies.

8
00:00:46,790 --> 00:00:50,690
I have two of them, in particular.

9
00:00:51,330 --> 00:00:58,930
One of them is low-voltage, up to 30 V, the other high-voltage up to 300 V.

10
00:00:59,390 --> 00:01:06,390
At first glance the voltage range is fine and suitable, but there are some problems.

11
00:01:07,070 --> 00:01:11,690
First, these supplies plug into the mains.

12
00:01:11,690 --> 00:01:17,450
And connecting to the mains guarantees us a connection with neutral.

13
00:01:17,950 --> 00:01:24,010
That is, the neutral wire in the mains is inevitably tied to ground.

14
00:01:24,530 --> 00:01:39,650
If we're building devices designed to extract energy relative to earth, then with these power supplies we won't get anything, since we're automatically tied to

15
00:01:39,650 --> 00:01:41,070
ground through neutral.

16
00:01:41,690 --> 00:01:53,690
You'd think we could exclude the ground connection, for example by powering these supplies through two transformers for isolation.

17
00:01:54,870 --> 00:01:58,990
But even in this case we still have a connection.

18
00:01:59,070 --> 00:02:03,750
It still slips through somehow and interferes with the work.

19
00:02:04,610 --> 00:02:09,450
Another option is to run the supplies through an inverter.

20
00:02:09,450 --> 00:02:16,070
Yes, this solution is good and solves the main earth-connection problem.

21
00:02:16,650 --> 00:02:17,890
But there's a catch.

22
00:02:18,550 --> 00:02:27,530
All our experiments in most cases involve pulse consumption from these power sources.

23
00:02:28,650 --> 00:02:38,790
And the effects accompanying these experiments are often so unpredictable that these power supplies behave totally inadequately.

24
00:02:39,450 --> 00:02:59,270
The controllers start behaving chaotically — output voltage jumps, output current jumps, and besides, the power supply starts operating in burst mode.

25
00:02:59,890 --> 00:03:05,450
That is, the influence on it from the output wires is that strong.

26
00:03:05,450 --> 00:03:11,610
Tried putting filters here — that also doesn't save us from this problem.

27
00:03:13,790 --> 00:03:16,310
Constantly wrong readings.

28
00:03:16,470 --> 00:03:32,850
And plus, when these blocks start operating in pulsed power supply mode, a burst-form signal appears at the output after the switch on the control device.

29
00:03:32,850 --> 00:03:40,890
That's additional frequency modulation, which obviously doesn't let us tune the system adequately.

30
00:03:41,350 --> 00:03:47,910
So I had to give up on these power supplies due to their unsuitability.

31
00:03:48,770 --> 00:03:57,230
Solutions like these are great for tuning electronics — they help me a lot.

32
00:03:57,230 --> 00:04:06,390
But unfortunately, for powering devices and for these experiments they aren't suitable.

33
00:04:06,950 --> 00:04:17,990
So I decided to develop this power supply that'll meet the tasks set.

34
00:04:18,910 --> 00:04:23,630
On the same topic, I can give the same advice about using an oscilloscope.

35
00:04:25,110 --> 00:04:33,450
Watching people's experiments — they connect the oscilloscope to the device and try to tune something.

36
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:43,990
Forgetting that the scope is plugged into the mains, and the scope's common wire is inevitably tied to neutral.

37
00:04:43,990 --> 00:04:56,410
And it turns out that even with a power supply we connect to the device and introduce the same problem.

38
00:04:57,930 --> 00:05:06,460
In Nikola Tesla's day there was a DC mains and no connection to neutral.

39
00:05:06,460 --> 00:05:14,800
Moreover, Tesla himself built devices that would let him work.

40
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:21,700
Like DC dynamo machines.

41
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:34,220
Such a dynamo machine gave an autonomous power source and could be brought to rotation with an external motor.

42
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:42,320
The thing is, all dynamo machines are essentially AC machines.

43
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:58,320
But if you make a dynamo machine with many contacts and do a collector takeoff, you can take potential from it at the peak of the AC wave.

44
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:04,840
And so get DC at the output — which is what he did.

45
00:06:05,540 --> 00:06:08,560
But back to our schematic.

46
00:06:10,160 --> 00:06:11,940
Let's look at it in more detail.

47
00:06:12,620 --> 00:06:21,320
First, power will come from a battery, which solves our ground-connection problem.

48
00:06:21,320 --> 00:06:40,080
Next, I added a relay element and a diode so that during our experiments with energetic effect couplings on the cheerful coil, we don't accidentally swap the power wires.

49
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:51,300
Such a polarity reversal would inevitably lead to switch failure and to the DC-DC converter that provides independent power.

50
00:06:53,380 --> 00:06:55,040
The solution is simple.

51
00:06:55,440 --> 00:07:07,420
We have a relay with normally-open contacts and a coil that creates the magnetic field, which attracts the contact and closes them.

52
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:18,320
If you install the diode in the correct direction, you can exclude wrong scheme connections.

53
00:07:18,320 --> 00:07:29,300
That is, when plus power is applied to the diode anode, current passes through it, the magnetic field forms naturally, and the contacts attract.

54
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:36,640
With reverse battery polarity, the contacts won't close.

55
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:47,100
Next I introduced a filter system — capacitors, choke — and then power goes to the power switches.

56
00:07:47,980 --> 00:07:52,580
I decided to go with a full-bridge schematic.

57
00:07:54,520 --> 00:08:03,440
Such a schematic will let us cleanly switch the primary winding and additionally use opto-isolation.

58
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:07,900
Four opto-drivers controlling the switches.

59
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:13,340
Also a galvanically isolated DC-DC converter.

60
00:08:13,340 --> 00:08:28,480
All this is done so that during our experiments there's no influence on the PWM controller or the drivers controlling the switches — which could lead to incorrect operation.

61
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:42,340
The whole circuit is fairly simple, but there'll be nuances in its build that I'll demonstrate along the way.

62
00:08:44,300 --> 00:08:53,680
We'll have current feedback so we can regulate current protection.

63
00:08:53,780 --> 00:09:02,240
A very important parameter so that if a short happens at the output, the system doesn't fail.

64
00:09:03,860 --> 00:09:09,360
And this point can be regulated, setting the trip threshold.

65
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:19,040
Pulse duration regulation will also be added, which ultimately controls the output voltage.

66
00:09:19,100 --> 00:09:32,360
That is, on each transformer tap we'll have voltage regulation from zero to the maximum that the turn count allows.

67
00:09:33,160 --> 00:09:45,140
The transformer will be made on a ferrite ring, and the secondary winding will have taps.

68
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:58,200
Here I schematically marked the taps that go to a switch — between taps you can switch, thereby regulating the maximum output voltage.

69
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:08,200
Voltage feedback can't be added here due to the scheme being too bulky.

70
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:18,900
We'll have to use the same switch to change the resistor circuits that set the feedback trip point.

71
00:10:18,900 --> 00:10:23,820
But I'll add this system to the PWM controller.

72
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:38,800
Say if we need to hold a constant voltage on some tap, we just take the potential from there, create a resistor divider, and feed it back.

73
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:45,020
Say we have a tested circuit for some transistor and know its parameters precisely.

74
00:10:45,020 --> 00:10:46,940
This can be done.

75
00:10:47,220 --> 00:10:54,020
And the main switching of voltage potential will be done with the switch.

76
00:10:55,060 --> 00:11:04,800
And the output voltage will be calculated by Ohm's law on the load — current times load resistance.

77
00:11:06,120 --> 00:11:21,240
Since our power will be pulsed, taken from this converter's output, the formula will be a little inaccurate, but it suits us fine.

78
00:11:23,880 --> 00:11:33,140
Before moving to building this circuit, we need to buy all the parts first.

79
00:11:33,140 --> 00:11:44,560
For now I found this switch at my place — a Soviet-era piece that perfectly suits us.

80
00:11:44,860 --> 00:11:52,060
It has a ceramic contact pad and quite a powerful terminal output.

81
00:11:52,060 --> 00:12:11,700
Here I drew where additional work on the terminals is needed — because right now if we switch, you can see that the switch, due to the contact pad width, temporarily shorts contacts.

82
00:12:11,840 --> 00:12:16,700
We need to get rid of that, and the switch will be fully suitable.

83
00:12:16,700 --> 00:12:34,080
The switch has 12 leads in a circle — one of them common, from which the supply voltage will be taken, and this petal does the switching.

84
00:12:35,800 --> 00:12:41,920
In this case I drew 12 leads, but I found an 11-lead switch.

85
00:12:42,920 --> 00:12:45,780
Not critical, suits us.

86
00:12:46,580 --> 00:12:52,940
Pick any here, whoever likes, for the output rating.

87
00:12:53,800 --> 00:13:05,030
Of the parts that set common system dimensions, I already have the ready DC-DC converter.

88
00:13:06,030 --> 00:13:14,370
The video on tuning and building it can be seen in the previous video clip on my channel.

89
00:13:15,550 --> 00:13:21,510
Made specifically for installation in this universal power supply.

90
00:13:22,190 --> 00:13:23,770
It'll go here.

91
00:13:25,090 --> 00:13:28,790
For all the other parts I go to the store.

92
00:13:29,790 --> 00:13:35,230
After buying them, we move to building.

93
00:13:35,870 --> 00:13:43,250
And at the same time, I'll count how much this universal power supply will cost in parts.

94
00:13:45,030 --> 00:13:47,150
Thanks to everyone who watched.

95
00:13:47,690 --> 00:13:49,210
See you in the next release.
